ations; and colonisation. After outlining the history of class relations, five chapters explore the ways in which social class consciously and unconsciously influenced a series of writers: Chaucer, Shakespeare, Behn, Rochester, Defoe, Duck, Richardson, Burney, Blake and Wordsworth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aSocial classes in literature. 0aSocial classeszGreat BritainxHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aClass conflict.  aClass consciousness.  aClass.  acommerce.  acommon.  aliterature.  arebellion.  arepresentation.  aservitude.  asocial mobility.1 aHadfield, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packagez978311128198840uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152612582840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526125828423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526125828/original  a978-3-11-128198-8  Manchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packageb2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles